<paragraph pageNumber="46">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="46">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="46">Metapleural</pageStartToken>
</pageStartToken>
lobes low and rounded. Anterior peduncle short and thick, with a tooth-like subpetiolar process. Petiolar node in profile with an angulate anterodorsal angle and a rounded posterodorsal angle; dorsum convex and not clearly defined. Postpetiole low and rounded. Head dorsum with a reticulate pattern and faint striations medially. Promesonotal dorsum with reticulate sculpture and fine longitudinal striations anteriorly. Propodeal dorsum reticulate with a few transverse striations and both nodes also reticulate. First gastral tergite smooth with a ring of short basal costulae. Dorsum of head with four longitudinal lines of fine acute hairs running between the eyes. The venter of head with two curved hairs and three straight hairs; pubescence present. Promesonotal dorsum with at least 10 erect hairs, acute apically. Propodeal dorsum with three erect hairs. Petiolar node with three pairs of hairs and postpetiole with four pairs of hairs. Gastral tergite and sternite with regularly spaced suberect hairs. Colour uniformly yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="46">Paratypes. HL 0.767-0.806, HW 0.598-0.610, HW1 0.664-0.686, CI 76-78, SL 0.561-0.570, SI 94, PW 0.425-0.462, ML 0.875-0.944, EL 0.226-0.236, EI 38-39 (2 of 2 measured).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="46">Same as the holotype, except number of hairs on the propodeum range from three tofour andonthe petiolar node range from three to four.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="46">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268199" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex ezantsi Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ezantsi">Nesomyrmex ezantsi</taxonomicName>
is similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268202" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex koebergensis Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="koebergensis">N. koebergensis</taxonomicName>
, N. njengelangaandN. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268200" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex inye Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inye">inye</taxonomicName>
. They share the following characteristics: petiolar node with rounded posterodorsal angle and anterodorsal angle either angulate or rounded; dorsum convex and not clearly defined. Dorsum of head with reticulate sculpture, sometimes overlaid by longitudinal rugulae. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268199" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex ezantsi Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ezantsi">N. ezantsi</taxonomicName>
is separated from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268206" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex njengelanga Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="njengelanga">N. njengelanga</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268200" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex inye Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inye">N. inye</taxonomicName>
by the propodeum which is armed with a pair of short triangular teeth (angulate in the latter two species with no clearly defined pair of short spines), and by being larger (HW 0.598-0.625 versus 0.507-0.559). 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268199" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex ezantsi Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ezantsi">N. ezantsi</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268202" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex koebergensis Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="koebergensis">N. koebergensis</taxonomicName>
by the pale colour (light brown in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268202" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex koebergensis Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="koebergensis">N. koebergensis</taxonomicName>
) and the dorsum of head which is predominantly smooth, with fine reticulate ground sculpture(reticulate and overlaid by longitudinal rugulae in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268202" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex koebergensis Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="koebergensis">N. koebergensis</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="46">Biology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="46">The three specimens were collected from pitfall traps in ‘Lambert 's Bay Strandveld ' (Mucina &amp; Rutherford 2006) vegetation.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="46">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="46">
In isi-Xhosa, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:268199" authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nesomyrmex ezantsi Mbanyana &amp; Robertson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ezantsi">ezantsi</taxonomicName>
means ‘below ' and is used here to refer to the fact that this species was collected on the coastal plain, in low-lying areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
